            <fr:title text="Weierstrass approximation theorem">Weierstrass approximation theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The set of polynomials on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[a, b]]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0002.xml" addr="FA-0002" title="Dense">dense</fr:link> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C([a, b])]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>Differs from Taylor's theorem, which states that a function with sufficiently many derivaties can be approximated locally by its <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0003.xml" addr="FA-0003" title="Taylor polynomial">Taylor polynomial</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The Weierstrass appoximation theorem applied to a continuous function, which need not be differentiable, and states that there exists a global polynomial approximation of the function on the whole interval <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[a,b]]]></fr:tex> (The sequence of approximating polynomials is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0004.xml" addr="FA-0004" title="Bernstein polynomials">Bernstein polynomials</fr:link>)</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
